body:
## What problem does this solve or what need does it fill?

We already have `insert_if`, e.g.,

```rust
commands.entity(entity).insert_if(Health(10), || !player.is_spectator())
```

## What solution would you like?

I have a need for `remove_if`, e.g.,

```rust
commands.entity(entity).remove_if::<Health>(|| health <= 0);
```

Like `insert_if`, this removes a bundle only if a certain condition is met.

The goal of having this method is to allow for chaining, e.g., in my game when leaving a battle, I need to tidy up regiment entity state, and it looks like this:

```rust
commands
        .entity(regiment_entity)
        .remove::<(
            // a bunch of components that are no longer valid outside of the battle state
        )>()
        // All deployed regiments need to be marked as deployed last battle.
        .insert_if(RegimentDeployedLastBattle, || is_deployed)
        // All dead regiments are no longer active.
        .remove_if::<RegimentActive>(|| roster.is_dead());
```

## What alternative(s) have you considered?

You can implement this in userland code using a trait extension, e.g.,

```rust
pub trait EntityCommandsExt<'w, 's> {
    /// Removes a bundle only if a condition is met.
    ///
    /// # Example
    /// ```
    /// # use bevy_ecs::prelude::*;
    /// #[derive(Component)]
    /// struct Health(u32);
    ///
    /// fn remove_if_dead(mut commands: Commands) {
    ///     commands.entity(entity)
    ///         .remove_if::<Health>(|| health <= 0);
    /// }
    /// ```
    fn remove_if<T: Bundle>(&mut self, condition: impl FnOnce() -> bool) -> &mut Self;
}

impl<'w> EntityCommandsExt<'w, '_> for EntityCommands<'w> {
    fn remove_if<T: Bundle>(&mut self, condition: impl FnOnce() -> bool) -> &mut Self {
        if condition() {
            self.remove::<T>();
        }
        self
    }
}
```

## Additional context

This has been [requested at least once on Discord](https://discord.com/channels/691052431525675048/749335865876021248/1235271915413966918).
